    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating is recommended for Maine?</h3>
    <p>For Maine's climate, a SEER (Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio) rating of 16-20 is recommended for optimal efficiency and cost-effectiveness. While the minimum SEER rating for new equipment is 14 (as of 2023), higher ratings provide better energy savings and comfort. SEER 16-18 systems offer the best value proposition for most Maine homes, providing significant energy savings without excessive upfront costs. For heat pumps, HSPF (Heating Seasonal Performance Factor) ratings of 9.0-10.0 are recommended for Maine's heating-dominated climate. Ductless mini-split systems often achieve SEER ratings of 20-25+ with HSPF ratings exceeding 10.0, making them highly efficient choices for Maine homes. Variable-speed compressors and advanced controls can further enhance efficiency and provide better humidity control during Maine's humid summer months.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Do solar panels work effectively in Maine winters?</h3>
    <p>Yes, solar panels work effectively in Maine winters, often performing better than expected due to several factors. Cold temperatures actually improve solar panel efficiency, as panels generate more electricity at lower temperatures. Snow can be beneficial by reflecting additional light onto panels, and modern panels are designed to shed snow naturally due to their smooth surface and slight warming from electricity generation. While winter days are shorter and sun angles are lower, Maine still receives substantial solar irradiation during winter months. A well-designed solar system with proper tilt angles (typically 30-45 degrees in Maine) will naturally shed most snow accumulation. Net metering allows homeowners to use excess credits generated during longer summer days to offset winter consumption, effectively balancing seasonal production variations throughout the year.</p>
  </div>
  
